\fs26 \cf2 Prepared 2026-07-17; expanded with context and recommendations 2026-07-20\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs27 \cf0 This questionnaire contains only decisions that remain unresolved after the first two rounds. The following are already treated as settled and are not being asked again: TECL-only; one user; always-on appliance; scheduled model-agnostic remote frontier agent; deterministic Gold verdict; autonomous candidate authoring; automatic Gold-to-leaderboard publication; no staging board or Trade Roster; normal active-strategy changes require Max; brokerage remains manual for 3.x; iOS is later; and only Max decides when 4.x begins.\
Each item now has four parts. "Context" explains what part of Montauk the decision controls and why it is being asked. "Question" states the choice in plain language. "Suggested answer" gives a concrete default you may accept. "Reasoning" explains the tradeoff behind that default. Type after "Your answer." If the recommendation matches your intent, "accept suggested answer" is enough.\
Some questions set owner policy; others identify a rule that must be designed and statistically calibrated during implementation. Where a number would be irresponsible to guess from preference alone, the suggested answer deliberately fixes the safety policy and requires the validation workstream to derive, simulate, version, and audit the exact number before production.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf3 Questionnaire process rule:
\f1\b0 \cf0  After Max finishes each questionnaire round, the reviewing agent must read the complete answers and update README.md, charter.md, decisions.md, and every affected pillar plan before preparing another round or a coding handoff. The answered questionnaire is preserved unchanged as source evidence; the active Markdown documents become the current project truth. Contradictions must be reconciled explicitly, and superseded decisions must remain marked in the decision log. No round is complete merely because the answer file exists.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa220\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs34 \cf0 A. Gold: the exact promise and economic gate\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-360\sa80\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs27 \cf0 1.	Gold wording\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa60\partightenfactor0

\fs26 \cf0 Context:
\f1\b0  This sentence defines the promise made whenever Montauk labels a configuration Gold. It governs the leaderboard, notifications, active-strategy eligibility, and how much trust you should place in the label.\

\f2\b Question:
\f1\b0  Should Gold promise that Montauk found no disqualifying failure under a named, reproducible contract, while explicitly avoiding a guarantee about future returns?\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa80\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Suggested answer:
\f1\b0  Accept this wording: "Gold is Montauk's highest current certification of an exact, frozen strategy configuration. Under a named validation-contract version and data vintage, it beat the defined TECL buy-and-hold benchmark on every required real-data horizon using the deployable execution model, passed every mandatory correctness, robustness, and search-wide anti-overfitting criterion, and remains current under Montauk's forward-monitoring rules. Gold means Montauk detected no disqualifying failure to the strongest extent supported by available evidence. It does not prove that overfitting is absent or guarantee any future call or return."\

\f2\b Reasoning:
\f1\b0  This is strong enough to mean "fit to trade under Montauk's best process" and precise enough to audit. An absolute statement that a strategy is not overfit or will succeed in every future market cannot be established from historical data.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa200\partightenfactor0

