\f2\b\fs27 \cf0 5.	Rolling B&H demotion\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa60\partightenfactor0

\fs26 \cf0 Context:
\f1\b0  This controls when new live evidence causes an existing Gold strategy to lose certification. Checking every day without persistence rules can eventually revoke a sound strategy because of one random crossing; waiting too long leaves a decayed strategy active.\

\f2\b Question:
\f1\b0  What policy should turn recent B&H underperformance into warning, stale, and revoked states?\

\f2\b Suggested answer:
\f1\b0  Use the same trailing five-year real-data horizon as Question 4. A first statistically meaningful breach creates a warning. Revoke only if the breach persists across two consecutive formal renewals separated by enough new observations under the minimum-evidence rule. Correctness, data-integrity, or replay failures still revoke immediately.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa80\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Reasoning:
\f1\b0  This adds hysteresis without ignoring deterioration. The exact confidence calculation and minimum new evidence should be simulated and audited by the validation workstream rather than guessed from preference.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\sa200\partightenfactor0

